name: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3550
Reason: 16-methyl-17-oxoandrost-5-en-3-yl acetate has a melting point that can be predicted by considering its structural components. The basic unit for this compound is androstane, which has a melting point of 106°C. The methyl group introduces a rigid structure and raises the melting point by approximately +10°C. The oxo group can participate in hydrogen bonding, which may contribute to the melting point by approximately +5°C. The acetate group can also contribute to the melting point due to its ability to form hydrogen bonds, estimated at around +10°C. The presence of two fused aromatic rings can also increase the melting point due to increased molecular rigidity and pi-stacking interactions, estimated at approximately +25°C for each additional fused ring.
